(19'') TA lib₃-bi E₁₁-ma ZI TUR', '', 1669, '(16’) In order for you to see the largest displacement: whatever is above the ‘knot’ and whatever is below the ‘kn[ot’] you accumulate [together] (17’) and you compute half of it, you add the difference to (it), you see the largest displacement.
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (1704, '(9'') šal-šiš U₄.MEŠ ša₂ ŠU₂ IGI u UŠ.MEŠ GABA.RI MU.AN.NA ana IGI-ka MUL₂.BABBAR T[A 9 ALLA EN 9 GIR₂.TAB]
(10'') 30 DANNA u₃ MU.AN.NA ana MU.AN.NA 11.⸢3⸣.20 U₄.MEŠ LA₂ u₃ 30 DAN[NA xxx]
(11'') KI ša₂ MUL₂.⸢BABBAR⸣ MU ana MU TAB ᵈUTU ina 30.45 U₄.MEŠ DU-ma 30.45 U₄.⸢MEŠ⸣ [u 11.3.20]
(12'') U₄.MEŠ ana UGU a-ḫa-miš₂ GAR.GAR-ma 41.48.20 U₄.MEŠ GABA.RI MU.AN.NA GAR-[an]', '', 1515, '(9'') Thirdly. In order for you to see the ‘days’ for setting (LA), appearance (FA) and stations, the equivalent of the ‘year’. Jupiter. The (region of the) small one: from [9 Cnc until 9 Sco] 10’30 (i.e. a) beru, and year by year you subtract 11;3,20 ‘days’, and 30 (i.e. one) ‘mile’ [...] (11’) you add [to] the position of Jupiter, year by year. The Sun proceeds in 30;45 (error for 30;55) ‘days’, and (12’) you accumulate 30;45 (error for 30;55) ‘days’ and [11;3,20] together, 41;48,20 (error for 41;58,20) ‘days’ you put down as the equivalent of the ‘year’.', 'BM 34081+ (BMAPT No. 18)', 'mathematical astronomy: procedure text', 'Babylon', 'ca. 250-50 BCE', 'Ossendrijver, M. 2016, Ancient Babylonian astronomers calculated Jupiters position from the area under a time-velocity graph, Science, 351, 482-484', 'http://dx.doi.org/10.1126/science.aad8085', 'rev. i 9''-12'' (P14)', 1793, '', '');
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (2606, 'ἐπιγνόντες τὴν τῶν ἑπτὰ θεῶν κείνησιν τὰ ὅλα σ̣[υ]νέχουσάν τε καὶ διοικοῦσαν ἀφ[θ]ό̣νως ἡμεῖν διὰ κανόνων αἰωνί̣ων ἀπέλειπ̣ον τὴν περὶ αὐτῶν γνῶσιν· ὅθεν ἕκαστον ψηφίσας ἀκριβῶς τέταχά σοι', '', 2273, '(The ancient Egyptians,) having recognized the motion of the seven (planetary) gods, which comprises and dispenses all things, have generously left us with the knowledge about them through perpetual tables: having precisely calculated each (planet’s position) by those means, I have set them out for you', 'P.Lond. I 130', 'horoscope', '', '81 CE', '(GH 81)', '', '6–19', 2668, '', '');
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (2607, 'ἐπιγνόντες τὴν τῶν ἑπτὰ θεῶν κείνησιν τὰ ὅλα σ̣[υ]νέχουσάν τε καὶ διοικοῦσαν ἀφ[θ]ό̣νως ἡμεῖν διὰ κανόνων αἰωνί̣ων ἀπέλειπ̣ον τὴν περὶ αὐτῶν γνῶσιν· ὅθεν ἕκαστον ψηφίσας ἀκριβῶς τέταχά σοι', '', 2274, '(The ancient Egyptians,) having recognized the motion of the seven (planetary) gods, which comprises and dispenses all things, have generously left us with the knowledge about them through perpetual tables: having precisely calculated each (planet’s position) by those means, I have set them out for you', 'P.Lond. I 130', 'horoscope', '', '81 CE', '(GH 81)', '', '6–19', 2669, '', '');
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (1905, 'In Arietis parte XX. ad Aquilonem versus oritur Haedus quem fert Auriga. Hoc sidere <oriente> quicumque nati fuerint, aliud ex fronte pollicentur, aliud latenter in moribus celant.', '', 869, 'Haedus rises at 20° Aries turned toward the north. He is the one Auriga carries. Those who are born with this star rising promise one thing from the front but hide another in their thoughts.', 'Firmicus Maternus, Mathesis', 'astrological compendium', 'Sicily', 'ca. 334 CE', 'Firmicus Maternus. 1897. Ivlii Firmici Materni Matheseos Libri VIII, ed. W. Kroll, F. Skutsch. Stuttgart: B. G. Teubner.', 'https://www.degruyter.com/document/doi/10.1515/9783110965186/html', '8.6.4', 1064, '2.296', '');
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (2142, 'Non est, inquit, species falsa nec duarum stellarum confinio ignis extentus, sed proprium sidus cometae est, sicut solis ac lunae.', '', 869, 'A comet, he says, is not an illusion or fire extending from the edges of two planets but is a celestial body on its own, like the sun and the moon.', 'Seneca, Natural Questions', 'philosophy', '', '62/63 CE', 'Seneca. Natural Questions, Volume II: Books 4-7. Translated by Thomas H. Corcoran. Loeb Classical Library 457. Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1972.', 'https://www.loebclassics.com/view/seneca_younger-natural_questions/1971/pb_LCL457.263.xml', '7.17.1', 2222, '262-263', '');
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (2579, 'Φασὶ δ᾽ οἱ σοφοί, ὦ Καλλίκλεις, καὶ οὐρανὸν καὶ γῆν καὶ θεοὺς καὶ ἀνθρώπους τὴν κοινωνίαν συνέχειν καὶ φιλίαν καὶ κοσμιότητα καὶ σωφροσύνην καὶ δικαιότητα, καὶ τὸ ὅλον τοῦτο διὰ ταῦτα κόσμον καλοῦσιν, ὦ ἑταῖρε, οὐκ ἀκοσμίαν οὐδὲ ἀκολασίαν.', '', 2251, 'And the wise men say, o Callicles, that sky and earth and gods and men are kept together by communion and friendship and propriety and temperance and justice, and the whole of this for this reason they call order ("cosmos"), my friend, not disorder nor dissoluteness.', 'Plato, Gorgias', 'philosophy', 'Athens', '4th century BCE', 'Plato. 1903. Plato. Platonis Opera, ed. J. Burnet. Oxford University Press.', 'http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Plat.+Gorg.+507e&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0177', '507e-508a', 2647, '', '');
INSERT INTO public.quotations VALUES (2608, 'Ἀλλὰ μὴ γεωμέτρης ἐπιθυμεῖς, ἔφη, γενέσθαι ἀγαθός, ὥσπερ ὁ Θεόδωρος; Οὐδὲ γεωμέτρης, ἔφη. Ἀλλὰ μὴ ἀστρολόγος, ἔφη, βούλει γενέσθαι; ὡς δὲ καὶ τοῦτο ἠρνεῖτο, Ἀλλὰ μὴ ῥαψῳδός; ἔφη· καὶ γὰρ τὰ Ὁμήρου σέ φασιν ἔπη πάντα κεκτῆσθαι.', '', 2268, '“Well, perhaps you want to be a good mathematician, like Theodorus?”1
